hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider a simplified model for the temperature dynamics of a two-component electronic device, where each component thermally interacts with the other and with a common heat sink. The state of the system is described by a vector $\mathbf{x}(t) = \begin{pmatrix} x_1(t) \\ x_2(t) \end{pmatrix}$, where $x_1(t)$ and $x_2(t)$ represent the temperature deviations of the first and second components, respectively, from the ambient temperature at time $t$. The system is unforced, meaning its evolution is governed solely by its initial state according to the homogeneous state-space equation $\dot{\mathbf{x}}(t) = A\mathbf{x}(t)$, where $A$ is a constant $2 \times 2$ matrix representing the thermal properties of the system.

The state transition matrix, $\Phi(t)$, which maps an initial state $\mathbf{x}(0)$ to the state at a later time $t$ via $\mathbf{x}(t) = \Phi(t)\mathbf{x}(0)$, has been determined for this system to be:
$$
\Phi(t) = \frac{1}{2}
\begin{pmatrix}
\exp(-t) + \exp(-3t)  \exp(-t) - \exp(-3t) \\
\exp(-t) - \exp(-3t)  \exp(-t) + \exp(-3t)
\end{pmatrix}
$$
where $t$ is time. Determine the system matrix $A$. Express your answer as a $2 \times 2$ matrix.
